That's a great question! While minimalist code is often praised for its conciseness and elegance, there are several compelling reasons—especially in educational and collaborative settings—why one might intentionally choose a more verbose and highly commented style.

Firstly, verbosity can be extremely beneficial for clarity. When a codebase is filled with detailed inline comments, each section of the code can explain not only what a specific segment is doing, but also why it is doing it in that particular way. This approach can help beginners and even experienced programmers who are diving into an unfamiliar section of code to quickly grasp the underlying logic without needing to decipher complex abstractions or tersely written expressions.

Secondly, redundant commenting sometimes serves as a self-documentation tool that facilitates debugging and future maintenance. For instance, consider a situation where a module handles data transformations. Rather than relying solely on method names or module organization, a programmer may insert detailed commentary at several steps to outline each transformation phase. Even if some comments may seem over-explanatory, having this redundant layer can significantly reduce the ramp-up time for new contributors or reviewers seeking to understand the code's intent.

Here’s a simplified example to illustrate a verbose coding style:

// Begin: Initialize the data processing module
// The following block is responsible for setting up the initial parameters
// It ensures that the input data is properly sanitized and prepared before processing
function initializeDataProcessing(inputData) {
    // Check if the input data array is not empty
    if (!inputData || inputData.length === 0) {
        // In case the input is invalid, throw an error with a clear message
        throw new Error('Invalid input data: The data array is empty or undefined.');
    }

    // Convert all input strings to lower case to standardize the data
    // This step is crucial for ensuring consistency during comparison operations
    let processedData = inputData.map(function(item) {
        // Convert item to string and then to lower case
        return String(item).toLowerCase();
    });

    // Return the processed and standardized data for further processing
    return processedData;
}
// End: Data processing initialization

In this snippet, the extra comments are intentionally added to explain each logical step. Although a minimalist programmer might condense this to only the essentials, here the redundancy helps elucidate the process in a step-by-step fashion.

Furthermore, verbose commenting is advantageous when developing educational materials or when mentoring less experienced programmers. It can serve as an in-depth guide that provides context and deeper insight into design decisions, algorithms, and best practices. In environments where the goal is to leave an easily accessible trail of reasoning and learning—such as academic settings or code review sessions—the benefits might outweigh the drawbacks of verbosity in terms of storage space or rapid scanning.

In summary, while minimalist design certainly has its merits, a complex, verbose coding style with redundant comments offers benefits in clarity, ease of maintenance, and educational value, which can be particularly valuable in collaborative or learning-focused environments.
